<H3> <TI>   EU Urges Freeze on Japanese Cars in Europe </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    EU Urges Freeze on Japanese Cars in Europe </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2604071494 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 25 Apr 
94 Morning Edition p 9--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2604071494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Brussels, 24 April -- There are again growing 
demands for restrictions on the total volume of Japanese cars, 
including those produced in Europe, within the European Union 
[EU]. In an interview with a NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN reporter, 
Association of European Automobile Manufacturers (ACEA) 
Secretary General Lenier [name as published] indicated that ACEA 
will ask the European Commission and other organizations 
concerned to take restrictive measures, saying: "The share of 
Japanese cars in the European market should be frozen." Similar 
opinions have also been voiced in the European Parliament. The 
1991 Japan-EU agreement does not impose restrictions upon 
Japanese cars produced in Europe. However, this issue is likely 
to remain a controversial problem in the future, because the 
European auto industry has been faced with business difficulties 
due to the prolonged economic slump. 
  The new ACEA chairman and secretary general took office this 
year. In his explanation of ACEA policies under the new 
leaders, Lenier touched on the Japanese car issue, and said: 
"The total volume of Japanese cars, including not only cars 
which are directly imported from Japan, but also those produced 
in Europe and imported from third countries (such as the United 
States) should be frozen." The ACEA has also presented this 
demand to the European Commission. 
  In accordance with the Japan-EU auto agreement, Japan has 
restricted its exports at a rate higher than the overall drop in 
European car sales. For example, in 1993 Japan set the quota of 
direct exports at 980,000 units, which was 18.5 percent lower 
than that of the previous year. 

</TEXT>

