<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hata To Visit Europe, Fill `Diplomatic Vacuum' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hata To Visit Europe, Fill `Diplomatic Vacuum' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2604041794 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 26 
Apr 94--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2604041794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [From NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN 26 April Morning Edition] </F>
  [Text] Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata will visit Italy, 
France, and Germany from 3 May, and make his debut on the 
international stage as a prime minister. 
  While this will be a trip undertaken on very short notice 
after former Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa's sudden decision 
to resign, it is deemed necessary to fill the diplomatic vacuum 
resulting from the domestic political confusion. Hata has also 
decided to push through with the European visit because of the 
need to establish a relationship of trust with leaders of 
European countries before the meeting of leaders of the advanced 
nations (Naples summit) in July. Furthermore, since cooperation 
with the European states is closely linked to a breakthrough in 
Japan-U.S. relations, the primary diplomatic task for Japan at 
the moment, the prime minister is expected to face a serious 
diplomatic challenge immediately after his assumption of office. 
  Hata is scheduled to hold talks with French President 
Francois Mitterrand, German Chancellor Helmut Kohl, and the new 
Italian prime minister during his European tour. However, the 
political situation in Italy remains volatile, and the new prime 
minister may not be chosen before Hata's visit. 
  This visit to Europe was originally planned for former Prime 
Minister Hosokawa during the Golden Week holidays [29 April-5 
May]. Hata has decided to comply with the original schedule as 
the successor to Hosokawa. 
  During his meetings with European leaders, Hata is expected 
to convey the message that, even after the change of political 
regimes, Japan's basic policies will remain unchanged under the 
new administration, and the Hosokawa administration's reform 
policy of market liberalization through deregulation and other 
measures will be maintained and further developed. 
  Russia's participation in the Naples summit will also be a 
major item on the agenda. Hata will also exchange views with 
the European leaders on the DPRK's development of nuclear 
devices, and the situation in the former Yugoslavia. 
  Both the Japanese ruling and opposition parties agree that 
the primary diplomatic issue for the new administration is how 
to effect a breakthrough in the stalled Japan-U.S. economic 
framework talks. The government would like to find a solution 
before the Japan-U.S. summit meeting to be held during the 
Naples summit. 
  In this connection, since the European countries have 
consistently taken the position that the numerical targets 
demanded by the United States may contribute to managed trade, 
the Japanese Government believes that "the prime minister's 
upcoming visit to Europe will be important for Japan's relations 
with the United States" (according to a Foreign Ministry source). 

</TEXT>

