<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hata, Perry Reconfirm Stance on DPRK Issue </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hata, Perry Reconfirm Stance on DPRK Issue </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2204044294 Tokyo KYODO in English 0419 GMT 22 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2204044294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 22 KYODO -- U.S. Defense Secretary 
William Perry and Foreign Minister Tsutomu Hata reconfirmed 
Friday that the international community should take a firm 
stance against North Korea's alleged nuclear weapons development 
while keeping doors open for dialogue, Foreign Ministry 
officials said. 
  Perry and Hata also agreed in a meeting at the Foreign 
Ministry on the importance of a diplomatic solution to the 
problem and close cooperation among Japan, the United States and 
South Korea, the officials said. 
  Hata told Perry if North Korea does not change its position, 
it is inevitable that the UN Security Council will have to 
discuss stricter measures, such as economic sanctions, against 
Pyongyang. 
  "In such a case, Japan intends to take a responsible stance 
within the framework of the constitution," Hata was quoted as 
saying, adding that close consultation with the U.S. is 
important in such circumstances. 
  He also pointed out that it is important for the Security 
Council to proceed with the discussions "gradually and 
step-by-step" so as to leave the doors open for dialogue with 
Pyongyang. 
  Perry and Hata also agreed on the importance of China's role 
in persuading North Korea to change its position, the officials 
said. 
  They agreed to closely watch developments between North 
Korea 
and the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) and the 
unofficial meetings with Washington, they said. 
  The officials declined to disclose the details of the 
75-minute meeting because of the sensitivity of the issue. 
  "I don't feel free to say (the contents of the meeting)," 
Perry told reporters after the talks. 
  Perry, who flew to Tokyo from Seoul Thursday night, was 
quoted as telling Hata that he does not think a military clash 
is likely on the Korean peninsula at the moment. 
  Perry said in Seoul Thursday that North Korea may be ready 
within weeks to remove enough plutonium from a nuclear reactor 
to build four or five nuclear bombs. 
  The IAEA inspectors were allowed into North Korea last month 
to check its nuclear facilities but were unable to determine if 
radioactive materials had been diverted to military purposes 
because Pyongyang blocked the inspectors from a key laboratory. 
  Pyongyang in March of last year announced its intention to 
withdraw from the Nuclear Nonproliferation Treaty. 
  On the bilateral front, Hata told Perry that relations with 
the U.S. will be an important "axis" for Japan's new government 
and that the country wants to deepen cooperation with 
Washington, the officials said. 
  Hata is the most likely candidate to succeed outgoing Prime 
Minister Morihiro Hosokawa. 
  Perry told Hata that the security arrangement between the 
U.S. and Japan is the pivot of security in East Asia, they said. 
  Hata told Perry Japan is studying whether the Theater 
Missile 
Defense (TMD) system is effective for Japan's security. 
  He said he wants continued talks with the U.S. on the 
matter. 
  The TMD system, an advanced version of the Patriot missile, 
would destroy incoming missiles while they are flying above or 
through the atmosphere. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-6955 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas080_a_94005" </HT>


