<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   DA Head Comments on Sanctions Against DPRK </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    DA Head Comments on Sanctions Against DPRK </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2604135894 Tokyo KYODO in English 1329 GMT 26 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2604135894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 26 KYODO -- Japan's Defense Agency 
[DA] Director General Kazuo Aichi and South Korea's Yi Pyong-tae 
agreed Tuesday [26 April] a diplomatic solution through talks is 
the best way to convince North Korea to allow full international 
inspections of its nuclear facilities, agency officials said 
Tuesday. 
  The officials said Aichi and Yi, who met at Defense Agency 
Headquarters in Tokyo, agreed that their respective countries, 
along with the United States, will maintain close cooperation. 
  Aichi told Yi that Japan is studying the problem as "a 
matter 
for Japan itself" and if the United Nations Security Council 
votes for sanctions against North Korea, Japan will "respond 
responsibly within the bounds of the Constitution," they said. 
  It is the first time a South Korean defense minister has 
visited Japan. 
  Aichi and Yi also agreed on exchange visits between training 
fleets and to work toward early implementation of procedures to 
prevent air accidents, officials said. 
  The International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) wants to 
inspect the spent fuel core of North Korea's Yongbyon reactor 
for evidence of whether any material has been diverted for 
possible use in a covert nuclear weapons development program. 
  On Monday, North Korea said it wants IAEA inspectors to 
monitor the refueling of its main nuclear reactor at the end of 
the month. 
  But an IAEA source said the agency needs to further sound 
out 
Pyongyang on an inspection mission, noting North Korea has yet 
to reply to the agency's inquiries. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

