<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hata on Prime Minister, Foreign Minister Jobs </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hata on Prime Minister, Foreign Minister Jobs </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2204023494 Tokyo KYODO in English 0150 GMT 22 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2204023494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 22 KYODO -- Foreign Minister Tsutomu 
Hata, who is certain to succeed outgoing Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa, indicated Friday [22 April] a prime minister should 
not serve concurrently as foreign minister. 
  Hata, 58, told a press conference the posts of prime 
minister 
and foreign minister should be held by different individuals to 
meet the demands of Japan's growing international role. 
  He pointed out that a great number of leaders from abroad 
now 
visit Japan and that the foreign minister should be able to 
travel overseas whenever necessary. 
  Hata said times have changed since the 1940s, when Prime 
Minister Shigeru Yoshida also served as foreign minister. 
  Heads of coalition parties will endorse Hata, who is also 
deputy prime minister and head of Shinseito, as a candidate for 
prime minister Friday afternoon following a deal struck early 
Friday by coalition representatives on a draft policy platform 
for a new cabinet. 
  Hata is certain to be elected prime minister in a Diet 
election expected Monday to select a successor to Hosokawa, who 
announced his resignation April 8. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

