<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hata Wants `International Trust', `High Quality' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hata Wants `International Trust', `High Quality' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2204083594 Tokyo KYODO in English 0801 GMT 22 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2204083594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 22 KYODO -- Foreign Minister Tsutomu 
Hata, the ruling coalition's candidate to succeed Prime Minister 
Morihiro Hosokawa, said Friday [22 April] that if elected 
premier, he wants to create a country that could win 
international trust. 
  Hata told a joint press conference with leaders of coalition 
parties that he will do his best to make Japan a nation of "high 
quality" which could be internationally trusted, understood and 
loved. 
  Calling himself "an inexperienced person" who hesitated to 
shoulder the burden of leading the nation, the 58-year-old Hata 
said, "but considering the support and the hardships of 
everyone, I decided to accept the recommendation, feeling my 
body tremble." 
  Prior to the news conference, the heads of the coalition 
parties endorsed a policy platform for a new cabinet and chose 
Hata, leader of Shinseito [Japan Renewal Party], as their 
candidate for prime minister. 
  Hata is expected to win the election for the premiership in 
plenary session votes of the House of Representatives and the 
House of Councillors on Monday. 
  The second coalition administration, led by Hata, will be 
launched later Monday. 
  The coalition agreement to field Hata, who is also deputy 
prime minister in the Hosokawa administration, followed weeks of 
wrangling over two vital policy issues -- tax reform and 
national security. 
  On April 8, Hosokawa, who became premier last August, 
abruptly announced he will resign to take responsibility for 
stalled Diet business over his alleged involvement in financial 
scandals. 
  Hata said he does not think there are cracks in the ruling 
coalition although the parties took two weeks to narrow 
differences over policies. The two weeks of debates were 
"meaningful," Hata said, because discussions on such matters as 
tax reform had to be done anyway by the end of June. 
  Hata also pointed out the need to enact the fiscal 1994 
budget as early as possible. 
  He said that although the ruling parties come from different 
backgrounds, the Hosokawa government was able to overcome 
various difficult problems, such as those involving the Uruguay 
Round of multilateral trade talks and electoral reform. 
  Tomiichi Murayama, chairman of the Social Democratic Party, 
said he recommended at the meeting of heads of parties earlier 
in the day that Hata is the "most suitable" person to succeed 
Hosokawa. The leaders of the parties unanimously agreed to 
field Hata as the candidate, he said. 
  Keigo Ouchi, head of the Democratic Socialist Party, said 
Hata is the most suitable considering his personality, knowledge 
and ability. 
  Komeito chairman Koshiro Ishida said the new government's 
main theme is to push ahead with reforms and an early enactment 
of the budget. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-6959 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas080_a_94009" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-080 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  23 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Editorials View Difficulties Facing Hata </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Editorials View Difficulties Facing Hata </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2304021194 Tokyo KYODO in English 0136 GMT 23 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2304021194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 23 KYODO -- Japan's major dailies on 
Saturday editorially welcomed the coalition's end to a two-week 
political paralysis by choosing Foreign Minister Tsutomu Hata as 
their candidate for prime minister, but also pointed out the 
difficulties lying ahead. 
  "Hata was considered the most likely candidate from the 
beginning," the ASAHI SHIMBUN said, citing the candidate's 
cabinet experience in Liberal Democratic Party-led governments 
and his "comparably high" popularity. 
  But "the Hata government sets sails while revealing big 
contradictions," the ASAHI editorial continued, pointing to 
major policy differences and animosity between Shinseito's 
[Japan Renewal Party] key strategist Ichiro Ozawa and leaders of 
the Social Democratic Party (SDP), the largest coalition party. 
  "Both (sides) were like oil and water from the very 
beginning," it said, adding that policy clashes over North Korea 
and tax increases seem inevitable. 
  "As before, Shinseito's No. 2 man Ozawa will play the major 
role, as so far Hata has failed to put his foot down on the 
intracoalition struggle," said the ASAHI editorial entitled, 
"Isn't It Prime Minister Ozawa?" 
  The NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN observed that with Hata's 
candidacy, 
"the antagonism between coalition parties has not been settled 
for the time being, and political instability characterized by 
political realignment is likely to continue." 
  After New Party Sakigake [Harbinger] split from its ally 
Japan New Party and pulled out of the coalition, "two poles" 
centering on the Shinseito-Komeito [Clean Government Party] bloc 
and the SDP have developed, the economic daily said. 
  It said Shinseito and the Buddhist-backed Komeito are 
devoted 
to a total overhaul of the tax system and tax hikes, which the 
NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN believes are necessary to finance the 
country's social security system. 
  The NIKKEI said it is doubtful whether the coalition will 
endorse "unconditionally" any steps the United Nations could 
take against North Korea in connection with its alleged nuclear 
weapons program. 
  "This will unavoidably narrow Japan's diplomatic range," the 
NIKKEI said. 
  "The rising tide for political realignment shows no signs of 
ebbing. Fires of change are smoldering," the YOMIURI said about 
the prospects of the coalition. It urged a "stable and strong 
government with common policy ideals and policies." 
  The YOMIURI, the nation's largest daily, said it would be 
better to make Hata's government a caretaker government to pass 
the fiscal 1994 budget, and then dissolve the House of 
Representatives for a general election. 
  The MAINICHI SHIMBUN regretted the missed opportunity for 
political realignment and the formulation of new policies which 
it anticipated from the formation of a new government. 
  "It will basically maintain the structure of the current 
coalition government," it said. 
  While urging the upcoming government to continue Hosokawa's 
reform drive, the MAINICHI doubts whether money politics will be 
rooted out. 
  "The political reforms focusing on a revival of the 
self-cleaning capacity of politics have come to an end before 
penetrating even below the surface," the MAINICHI said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-6960 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas080_a_94010" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-080 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  24 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kono Criticizes Coalition for `Rotating Power' </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Kono Criticizes Coalition for `Rotating Power' </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2404093694 Tokyo KYODO in English 0927 GMT 24 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2404093694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Okayama, April 24 KYODO -- Opposition leader Yohei 
Kono criticized the ruling coalition Sunday [24 April] for 
spending its energy only on trying to maintain the alliance and 
for rotating power within the coalition. Kono, president of the 
Liberal Democratic Party (LDP), accused the coalition's core 
party Shinseito [Japan Renewal Party] in particular of failing 
to take due process under parliamentary democracy. "Never lead 
Japan's politics on a wrong path," he said. [sentence as 
received] 
  Kono did not go into specifics, although he was apparently 
referring to controversies involving issues such as taxes. 
  In early February, Hosokawa announced plans to implement a 6 
trillion yen tax cut and also to replace the 3 percent 
consumption tax with a 7 percent "national welfare tax." 
  The new tax proposal, which was soon scrapped, was widely 
criticized as being hastily put out and being done abruptly in a 
closed-door meeting. 
  Kono spoke at an LDP-sponsored fund-raising event in 
Okayama, 
some 730 kilometers west of Tokyo, on the eve of the Diet's 
election Monday of Shinseito head Tsutomu Hata as Japan's new 
prime minister. 
  Hata is foreign minister in the cabinet of outgoing Prime 
Minister Morihiro Hosokawa. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

