<H3> <TI>   `Main Points' of Statement Noted </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Main Points' of Statement Noted </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2504172694 Tokyo KYODO in English 1718 GMT 25 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2504172694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 26 KYODO -- The following are main 
points of a statement issued by Social Democratic Party Chairman 
Tomiichi Murayama: 
  -- The SDP did its utmost to secure the election of Tsutomu 
Hata as prime minister of Japan. 
  -- We expected Hata to convene a meeting of leaders of the 
coalition parties and express the basic position of a new 
cabinet. But no such request was made. 
  -- While we were waiting, secret preparations were made to 
establish a new unified parliamentary group "Kaishin" 
(Innovation) without consulting the SDP. 
  -- The establishment of the new group infringes the 
relationship of trust among the coalition parties. 
  -- After intensive discussions, we signed the coalition 
policy accord just prior to the establishment of a new 
government. This was the result of sincere efforts we had made 
from the standpoint of continuing the reform policies launched 
by the Hosokawa cabinet and of maintaining the framework of the 
coalition. 
  -- It was agreed upon that a change in the formation of the 
government must be discussed among coalition parties. It is 
unpardonable for specific parties or individuals to ignore those 
processes and destroy the framework arbitrarily. 
  -- The SDP cannot permit such arbitrary maneuvering by a new 
coalition government which amplifies the sense of distrust among 
the people in politics. Therefore, the SDP cannot remain as a 
member of the coalition, is determined to promote political 
reform together with the people, and cannot respond to calls for 
formation of a new cabinet. However, we will make every effort 
to help the economy recover, including the enactment of the 
fiscal 1994 budget as promised. 

</TEXT>

