<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Rough Going' Expected on Budget </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `Rough Going' Expected on Budget </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2504174094 Tokyo KYODO in English 1731 GMT 25 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2504174094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 26 KYODO -- The departure of the 
Social Democratic Party (SDP) from the ruling coalition is 
expected to make it extremely hard for the new administration of 
Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata to steadily carry out economic 
policies. SDP chairman Tomiichi Murayama said his party will do 
whatever it can to enact the fiscal 1994 national budget when he 
said at a news conference early Tuesday [26 April] morning that 
the party will leave the coalition. 
  However, rough going is expected in Diet deliberations on 
the 
budget, political sources said. 
  Murayama told reporters the SDP will consider a recent 
coalition agreement on tax reform, including a hike in indirect 
tax, "with a clean slate." 
  This indicates discussions on tax reform may hit a snag, 
making it difficult for the Hata administration to pass the 1994 
budget bill through the Diet before the July summit of the Group 
of Seven economic powers in Naples, Italy, political analysts 
said. 
  They forecast the SDP may be strongly opposed to a hike in 
the 3 percent consumption tax to finance 6 trillion yen worth of 
cuts in income and residential taxes for the current fiscal year. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

