<H3> <TI>   Government `Inauguration' Delayed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Government `Inauguration' Delayed </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2504162194 Tokyo KYODO in English 1611 GMT 25 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2504162194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 26 KYODO -- Newly elected Prime 
Minister Tsutomu Hata failed to launch a cabinet Monday [25 
April] after the abrupt formation of a new 130-legislator 
parliamentary group enraged the largest party in the coalition, 
coalition officials said. 
  The unexpected development has delayed until after Tuesday 
the inauguration of a new government. 
  The intracoalition standoff delayed the process of forming a 
new cabinet and the subsequent imperial attestation ceremony at 
the Imperial Palace in the presence of Emperor Akihito, they 
said. 
  Hata said in a telephone message Monday night to Eiichi 
Nakamura, representative of the Democratic Reform Party, a small 
political party in the House of Councillors affiliated with 
Japan's largest trade union organization, the Japanese Trade 
Union Confederation (Rengo), that he will complete the formation 
of his new cabinet by the early hours of Tuesday. 
  Hata also said he would have to make fairly major 
alterations 
in the personnel lineup of the cabinet of former Prime Minister 
Morihiro Hosokawa, which resigned en masse Monday morning. 
  The Social Democratic Party (SDP), with 74 members in the 
House of Representatives, reacted strongly to the sudden 
establishment of the new parliamentary group in the lower house, 
from which it is excluded. 
  Coalition dissension intensified a few hours after the Diet 
voted Shinseito leader Hata, 58, as new prime minister in place 
of Hosokawa. 

</TEXT>

