<H3> <TI>   Hata Appeals to SDP To Remain </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hata Appeals to SDP To Remain </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2504190894 Tokyo KYODO in English 1859 GMT 25 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2504190894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 26 KYODO -- Newly elected Prime 
Minister Tsutomu Hata early Tuesday regretted the decision by 
the Social Democratic Party (SDP) to leave the governing 
coalition and appealed to the party to give up the decision. 
  However, Hata defended the formation of the 130-legislator 
parliamentary group which excludes the SDP, the largest party in 
the coalition, drawing the latter's ire, saying, "The formation 
does not constitute any betrayal" of the socialists. 
  In a press interview at the prime minister's official 
residence, Hata said such a parliamentary convergence is 
necessary to enable Japan to deal with the difficult times 
ahead, explaining, "unless we have such a group, coalition 
parties will not be able to cope with the difficult problems and 
act in solidarity." 

</TEXT>

