<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hata Seeks Meeting With Murayama </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hata Seeks Meeting With Murayama </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2604055494 Tokyo KYODO in English 0540 GMT 26 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2604055494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 26 KYODO -- Newly elected Prime 
Minister Tsutomu Hata called Tuesday on Social Democratic Party 
(SDP) [Social Democratic Party of Japan -- SDPJ] Chairman 
Tomiichi Murayama to meet him, in a last-ditch effort to 
persuade the SDP to stay in the coalition. 
  However, Hata indicated to reporters that he seeks to form a 
new cabinet Tuesday even without the SDP, saying, "we cannot 
spend so much time." 
  A coalition government without the SDP would be a minority 
one. 
  There are also moves going on to entice elements of the 
largest opposition Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) into the 
coalition, political sources said. 
  Leaders of the ruling coalition met at the prime minister's 
official residence to discuss the SDP's decision to quit the 
alliance and decided that Hata should urge Murayama to hold 
talks, coalition officials said. 
  An emergency meeting of the SDP's Central Executive 
Committee 
Tuesday morning endorsed a decision taken earlier in the day by 
its top officials to quit the coalition, party officials said. 
The SDP was the largest party in the coalition. 
  Murayama announced at a hastily arranged news conference 
after a meeting by top executives that the party decided to 
leave the alliance because it cannot approve of an abrupt move 
by some coalition partners to establish a new 130-legislator 
parliamentary group in the House of Representatives, which 
excludes the SDP. 
  The new parliamentary caucus, named "Kaishin (innovation)," 
was formed hours after Hata was elected prime minister by the 
Diet on Monday afternoon. 
  It comprises Shinseito [Japan Renewal Party], the Japan New 
Party, and the Democratic Socialist Party (DSP), as well as two 
splinter groups that recently defected from the LDP -- the 
Liberal Party and Kaikaku No Kai. 
  The Liberal Party was established by seven rebels who left 
the LDP to support veteran LDP politician Michio Watanabe's 
aborted attempt to seek the premiership. The party did not sign 
a policy platform agreed upon last Friday by the coalition heads 
for forming a new government. 
  Murayama criticized the formation of the new parliamentary 
bloc as destroying the coalition structure. 
  "It is outrageous for a certain political party or an 
individual to have destroyed the current combination of 
coalition parties while ignoring the process of the 
accord-building," Murayama said, apparently referring to 
Shinseito Secretary General Ichiro Ozawa, the chief coalition 
strategist. 
  The strength of the coalition excluding the SDP stands at 
182 
seats, compared with the 206 of the LDP in the 511-seat lower 
house. 
  The SDP, which held six cabinet posts in the government of 
Morihiro Hosokawa, Hata's predecessor as premier, has 74 members 
in the lower house. 
  New party Sakigake [Harbinger], which has 15 members in the 
lower house, has refused to join the new parliamentary group. 
Sakigake, led by Masayoshi Takemura, chief cabinet secretary in 
the Hosokawa cabinet, voted for Hata in the Diet but has vowed 
not to take a cabinet post. 
  Hata's policy speech to the Diet scheduled for Tuesday 
afternoon was postponed because of the delay of forming the new 
cabinet, Diet officials said. 
  The seven-party coalition government led by Hosokawa forced 
the LDP out of its 38-year-old grip on power last August. 

</TEXT>

