<H3> <TI>   Ouchi Hints at Disbanding of New Diet Bloc </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Ouchi Hints at Disbanding of New Diet Bloc </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2604133394 Tokyo KYODO in English 1312 GMT 26 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2604133394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 26 KYODO -- Democratic Socialist Party 
(DSP) Chairman Keigo Ouchi said Tuesday [26 April] he is ready 
to ask other coalition partners to disband a new 130-legislator 
parliamentary bloc if that could convince the Social Democratic 
Party (SDP) to reverse its decision to quit the ruling coalition. 
  "If the (presence of the) new parliamentary group hampers 
the 
maintenance of the coalition framework, we are ready to disband 
it," Ouchi said in a TV program. Ouchi on Monday proposed the 
creation of the new parliamentary bloc called Kaishin 
(Innovation) to support newly elected Prime Minister Tsutomu 
Hata. 
  After five parties and groups formed the bloc without the 
SDP, which was kept in the dark over the move, the SDP, the 
largest force in the coalition, decided to withdraw from the 
coalition. The SDP's decision plunged Japan's political world 
into confusion, with the possibility that Hata will be forced to 
form a minority government. 
  "We will not place any conditions before accepting a 
possible 
return of the SDP into the coalition fold," Ouchi said. 

</TEXT>

