<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Review of Oil-Burning Power Plant Policy Urged </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Review of Oil-Burning Power Plant Policy Urged </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2204131994 Tokyo KYODO in English 1202 GMT 22 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2204131994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 22 KYODO -- Japan will review its 
long- standing policy of banning construction of oil-burning 
thermal power plants, a senior energy agency official said 
Friday [22 April]. 
  Elements of a revised policy will be included in a report 
forecasting Japan's long-term energy demand and supply toward 
the next century, set for release on June 21, said the official 
at the Natural Resources and Energy Agency, who declined to be 
named. 
  The official said the review is in response to requests by 
power firms to "fine-tune" the amount of energy supply during 
the peak energy usage time in summer. 
  Under the adjusted policy, the agency will allow renovation 
of outmoded oil-burning thermal power plants, the official said. 
  But building completely new facilities will still not be 
allowed under the terms of the June report, he said. 
  Construction of new oil-fired thermal power plants has been 
prohibited since 1980 as part of efforts to promote the 
development of alternative energy following the second oil 
crisis in the late 1970s. 

</TEXT>

