<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   `World Public' Denounces U.S. Moves </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    `World Public' Denounces U.S. Moves </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2604010494 Pyongyang KCNA in English 2148 GMT 25 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2604010494 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, April 25 (KCNA) -- World public is 
strongly denouncing the U.S. belligerent moves on the Korean 
peninsula. 
  The chairman of the Denmark-the Democratic People's Republic 
of Korea Friendship Association in his report at a meeting of 
the executive committee of the association held in Copenhagen on 
April 7 said that the United States in the past deployed nuclear 
and other weapons of mass destruction in South Korea on the plea 
of thwarting "threat from the North" and today it is bringing 
forward the "nuclear issue" of Korea as a pretext to keep hold 
on South Korea. 
  If the United Nations wanted to call something in question, 
it should have accused the United States of shipping nuclear and 
other mass destruction weapons into South Korea in violation of 
the Korean Armistice Agreement and called attention to the 
non-compliance with the UN resolution on the withdrawal of 
foreign troops. 
  The African regional committee for the study of the chuche 
idea in a statement April 13 said that the nuclear issue of the 
Korean peninsula can be resolved only through talks between the 
DPRK and the U.S. as it originated from the U.S. deployment of 
nuclear weapons in South Korea and its nuclear threat to the 
DPRK, and the [word indistinct] in an appeal on April 14 urged 
the U.S. administration to come out to a direct dialogue with 
the DPRK before it is too late. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

