<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. `Pressure' in Philippines Condemned </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    U.S. `Pressure' in Philippines Condemned </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2304110894 Pyongyang KCNA in English 1030 GMT 23 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2304110894 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, April 23 (KCNA) -- A Japanese newspaper 
April 21 quoted sources of the Foreign Ministry of the 
Philippines as saying on April 19 that the U.S. ambassador to 
the Philippines was putting pressure through President Fidel 
Ramos on Filipino Foreign Minister Roberto Romulo to refrain 
from remarks critical of the U.S. policy toward the Korean 
peninsula. 
  The foreign minister criticized the U.S. policy, saying that 
the strong hope of the United States for quick satisfaction 
cannot be said to be a diplomatic policy and that the U.S. needs 
to relax its confrontational attitude toward North Korea and 
must continue to work for a peaceful settlement. 
  The U.S. ambassador expressed disappointment at this 
criticism and complained that he did not expect such criticism 
from an ally. 
  The ambassador, impudently enough, urged Filipino President 
Fidel Ramos to order the foreign minister to stop such remarks 
as putting the U.S. in an awkward position in the discourse 
about the Korean peninsula. 
  This is an infringement on the sovereignty of the 
Philippines. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-7017 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas080_c_94008" </HT>


