<H3> <TI>   ROK Opposition Party Rejects Sanctions </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    ROK Opposition Party Rejects Sanctions </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2204110094 Pyongyang KCNA in English 1035 GMT 22 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2204110094 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, April 22 (KCNA) -- Yi Ki-taek, president 
of South Korea's largest opposition Democratic Party, at a press 
conference in Washington Wednesday said the position of his 
party was to oppose the imposition of "sanctions" on the North 
for nuclear inspection and find a peaceful solution to the 
nuclear issue, a foreign news report said. 
  He said diplomatic means was the only way to ease the 
tensions on the Korean peninsula. He hoped the nuclear issue 
could be settled peacefully through DPRK-USA talks. 
  He declared that the Democratic Party did not welcome the 
deployment of Patriot missiles in South Korea. 

</TEXT>

