<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Japan's Qualifications for UNSC Seat Doubted </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Japan's Qualifications for UNSC Seat Doubted </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2604051494 Pyongyang KCNA in English 0506 GMT 26 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2604051494 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> ["Is Japan Qualified?" -- KCNA headline] </F>
  [Text] Pyongyang, April 26 (KCNA) -- A ranking official of 
the Japanese Foreign Ministry said some time ago that Japan 
should express its desire to be a permanent member of the United 
Nations Security Council [UNSC] "more explicitly than before" to 
the international community. 
  Commenting on this, NODONG SINMUN today says that, in 
seeking 
permanent membership of the Security Council, Japan intends to 
gratify its dominationist desire through military intervention 
in the disputes of the world and have its past crimes hushed up 
at any cost. 
  The news analyst says: 
  A high-placed authority of the Japanese Government has gone 
the length of making Japan appear a permanent member of the 
Security Council, insolently claiming that "Japan has so far 
played a role equal to a permanent member of the U.N. Security 
Council." 
  Such behaviour of Japan is a mockery of the international 
community, which shows its brazenness. 
  Japan is not qualified to be a permanent member of the 
Security Council. 
  By unleashing World War II, Japan destroyed world peace and 
security and imposed big disasters on the peoples of many 
countries. For these crimes, it is specified as a "hostile 
state" in the U.N. charter. 
  Still more grave is that Japan has set it as its state 
strategy to revive its policy of aggression of the past. 
  The policy of aggression of Japan which is hastening its 
conversion into a military power and its nuclear armament after 
paving the way for troops' dispatch overseas, poses a big threat 
to the peace in Asia and the world. 
  Japan is racing headlong toward aggression, not breaking 
with 
its imperialist past. How can it be a permanent member of the 
U.N. Security Council whose mission it is to ensure peace and 
security of the world? 
  If Japan is made a permanent member, it will mean 
overlooking 
Japan's failure to liquidate its past and encouraging it to 
commit past crimes again. 
  Before coveting permanent membership, Japan must 
conscientiously repent of its mistake, honestly discharge its 
responsibility for apology and compensation and stop pursuing 
aggression and war. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

