Daily Report 
<DATE1>  19 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   UNHCR Willing To Help With DPRK Loggers </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UNHCR Willing To Help With DPRK Loggers </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK1904082694 Seoul YONHAP in English 0706 GMT 19 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1904082694 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, April 19 (YONHAP) -- The United Nations High 
Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) has notified the South Korean 
Government of its willingness to cooperate in Seoul's bid to 
resettle fleeing North Korean loggers, a senior Foreign Ministry 
official said Tuesday. 
  In reply to a government request, the UNHCR praised Seoul's 
decision to allow the loggers to resettle in South Korea and 
expressed its readiness to cooperate, the official said. 
  He said the ministry asked the UNHCR headquarters in Geneva 
last Friday to confirm the identity of loggers who escaped from 
North Korean camps in Siberia and give them refugee status. 
  The UNHCR will instruct its Moscow office to cooperate in 
offering refugee status to the escapees late this week when it 
finishes a study on how to protect, temporarily accommodate, and 
look into the backgrounds of, the escapees and what to do with 
the loggers after giving them refugee status. 
  The government told the UNHCR about human rights conditions 
at the North Korean logging camps in Siberia and about escapees 
from the camps, and asked for cooperation in resettling the 
loggers in South Korea. 
  The government plans to allow those who have been clearly 
identified to come here directly after consultations with the 
Russian Government, while those requiring further identification 
procedures must be screened by the UNHCR to determine their 
refugee status. 
  Hundreds of North Korean loggers have escaped from Siberian 
logging yards, testifying later to rampant human rights 
violations inside the camps. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

