<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   DPRK `Refusal' To Revise Russian Treaty Noted </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    DPRK `Refusal' To Revise Russian Treaty Noted </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2504100594 Seoul KYONGHYANG SINMUN in Korean 25 April 94 p 
2 </F>

<F P=103> SK2504100594 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KYONGHYANG SINMUN </F>
<F P=105>  Korean </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] North Korea and Russia have agreed to revise the 
"North Korea-Russia Friendship, Cooperation, and Mutual 
Assistance Treaty," involving the abrogation of a provision on 
automatic military intervention, to meet a change in the 
situation at home and abroad. However, due to North Korea's 
refusal, it has been dragged on over a year even without having 
consultations. 
  According to a diplomatic source on 24 April, then Russian 
Vice Foreign Minister Georgiy Kudnadze, current ambassador to 
the ROK, visited Pyongyang in February, 1993. In the talks with 
North Korean Foreign Minister Kim Yong-nam, Kudnadze brought 
forth the issue regarding the revision and agreed with the North 
side to fully revise the treaty in conformity with the current 
situation. Nonetheless, North Korea has so far showed no 
reaction. 
  In particular, upon Russia's proposal, Russia and North 
Korea 
reached an agreement to abrogate or re-interpret the so-called 
provision on automatic military intervention which stipulates 
that a country should automatically render military assistance 
to the other country that is invaded since the provision is a 
relic of the Cold- War era. However, North Korea has declined 
to take up the issue. 
  As regards to this, a government official predicted: 
"Chances 
are very slim that the discussions will soon be made on the 
issue." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-7069 </DOCNO>
