<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Seoul-Tokyo Goodwill Naval Fleet Planned </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Seoul-Tokyo Goodwill Naval Fleet Planned </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   SK2604031494 Seoul YONHAP in English 0258 GMT 26 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK2604031494 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, April 26 (YONHAP) -- South Korea and Japan 
will agree to exchange goodwill Naval fleet visits and military 
flight schedules over the open seas. 
  The agreement is being sealed by Defense Minister Yi 
Pyong-tae, who left for Tokyo Tuesday morning as the first South 
Korean defense minister to visit Japan, when he meets his 
Japanese counterpart for one and a half hours later in the 
afternoon, a Defense Ministry official said. 
  Under the pact, South Korean Naval vessels will call at a 
Japanese port in the fall and a Japanese fleet will make a 
return call sometime thereafter. 
  Yi and his Japanese counterpart will also discuss regional 
security in Northeast Asia, including the international row over 
North Korea's suspected nuclear arms program, and ways to 
increase bilateral military exchanges, the official added. 
  During his stay in Tokyo, Yi will pay a courtesy call on new 
Japanese Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata and his foreign minister. 
  He will fly to Moscow on Thursday -- also becoming the first 
South Korean defense minister to visit Russia -- and remain 
there until next Tuesday. He is scheduled to meet with Russian 
Defense Minister Pavel Grachev to discuss increasing personnel 
and other military exchanges and sign the Korea-Russia 1994-95 
memorandum of understanding on military exchanges. 
  From Russia he will proceed to Germany to meet with his 
German counterpart on expansion of the Korea-Germany military 
technology exchange program and to visit major military 
installations. 
  Yi will return home on Thursday next week, winding up his 
11-day tour of the three countries. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

