<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hata Urges End to Trade Row With U.S. by Jul </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Hata Urges End to Trade Row With U.S. by Jul </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2204023094 Tokyo KYODO in English 0209 GMT 22 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2204023094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 22 KYODO -- Foreign Minister Tsutomu 
Hata called Friday [22 April] for a resolution of Japan's trade 
dispute with the United States by July, when the Group of Seven 
(G-7) industrialized nations is set to hold a summit in Naples. 
  Hata, who is certain to become the next prime minister, told 
a press conference he believes Japan and the U.S. could solve 
the trade row because he and U.S. Trade Representative Mickey 
Kantor were able to understand "what the problems are" when they 
met last week in Marrakech, Morocco. 
  Japan will hammer out the second package of market-opening 
measures by June and the U.S. also has been making efforts to 
create products meeting Japanese demands, he said. 
  Hata said Japan must spontaneously take steps to open its 
markets because this will not only reduce its huge surplus with 
the U.S. but will also contribute to the improvement of people's 
lives and inject dynamism into the domestic economy. 
  Tokyo and Washington have been unable to resume the trade 
"framework" that broke down in February over failure to iron out 
differences on the "objective criteria" for foreign access to 
Japanese markets. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

