<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Perry Discusses DPRK Nuclear Issue in Speech </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Perry Discusses DPRK Nuclear Issue in Speech </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2204061594 Tokyo KYODO in English 0514 GMT 22 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2204061594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 22 KYODO -- U.S. Defense Secretary 
William Perry warned Friday that North Korea will soon be able 
to produce "10 to 12" nuclear bombs a year. 
  "Left unchecked (North Korean) nuclear capability would 
disrupt the security of all Asia," he said in a speech at the 
Foreign Correspondents' Club of Japan in Tokyo. 
  Perry said in Seoul on Thursday that intelligence reports 
indicate North Korea will have the plutonium required for "four 
to five" nuclear weapons very soon, but his speech Friday is 
apparently the first time he has indicated a north korean 
nuclear arsenal could grow so quickly. 
  Before his press club appearance, Perry met with Foreign 
Minister Tsutomu Hata, and Foreign Ministry officials said the 
two renewed their determination to get tough on the North Korean 
nuclear issue. 
  Hata and perry also emphasized the need for a diplomatic 
solution to the nuclear standoff, the officials said, adding the 
two also confirmed that Tokyo and Washington will continue to 
maintain close contact with South Korea. 

</TEXT>

