Daily Report 
<DATE1>  25 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Watanabe Continues To Seek Shinseito Cooperation </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Watanabe Continues To Seek Shinseito Cooperation </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW2704204194 Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN in Japanese 25 Apr 
94 Morning Edition p 2--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW2704204194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] On 24 April, Michio Watanabe, former deputy prime 
minister and foreign minister of the Liberal Democratic Party, 
commented about his future cooperation with Shinseito [Japan 
Renewal Party]. He said: "If our policy goals are the same, it 
is natural for us to begin by first joining our hands to do that 
which is beneficial for Japan." Watanabe made his remarks in an 
appearance on a program broadcast by FNN TV Network the same 
day. He indicated he plans to continue seeking possible 
cooperation with Shinseito Secretary General Ichiro Ozawa and 
other party members. 
  Watanabe disclosed his views, saying: "Under a single-seat 
constituency system, there will eventually emerge two large 
political parties." He then pointed out: "I doubt whether the 
current coalition alliance would merge into a single party." He 
thus disclosed his expectation that those advocating similar 
policies will eventually form an alliance. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

