<F P=100> Vietnam </F>
<H3> <TI>   Strike Reported at Southern Clothing Firm </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Strike Reported at Southern Clothing Firm </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   BK2604140694 Hong Kong AFP in English 0858 GMT 26 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> BK2604140694 </F>
<F P=104>  Hong Kong AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Hanoi, April 26 (AFP) -- Workers at a private 
clothing firm struck last week in the southern province of Song 
Be, the area most affected by labor unrest in Vietnam, the trade 
union newspaper Lao Dong said Tuesday. 
  Some 150 workers from the Song Be Garment Export Co. stopped 
work for two hours Thursday in favor of overtime payments and 
the lowering of production levels required by management. 
  Company director Le Thi Bich Ngoc, rejected the strikers' 
demands, saying they could resign if they felt they were unable 
to meet the production demands. 
  The strikers plan to stop work again by the end of the week 
if their demands were not met. 
  The latest strike followed similar action earlier this month 
by 2,500 workers at the state-run peanut firm Thanh Le against 
working conditions and low salaries. 
  Labor unrest in southern Vietnam has increased in recent 
months, particularly in companies controlled by foreign firms. 
  Vietnam plans to adopt a labor code in May in which the 
right 
to strike is to be defined for the first time. 

</TEXT>

