<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Biographical Sketches of New Cabinet Members </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Biographical Sketches of New Cabinet Members </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Foreign Minister Koji Kakizawa </H4>

<F P=102> OW2804094994 Tokyo KYODO in English 0922 GMT 28 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2804094994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 28 KYODO -- Newly appointed Foreign 
Minister Koji Kakizawa is head of the new party "Jiyuto" 
(Liberal Party), a coalition bloc, and is credited for his 
expertise in financial and foreign affairs. Kakizawa, 60, 
replaced Tsutomu Hata in the post, the latter having been 
elected as prime minister. 
  Conversant in both English and French, he has demonstrated 
great interest in foreign affairs, having served as chairman of 
the House of Representatives Foreign Affairs Committee in 1990 
and as parliamentary vice foreign minister from 1991 to 1993 
under then Prime Minister Kiichi Miyazawa. 
  During that latter stint, he visited Mozambique to pave the 
way for deployment of Japanese U.N. peacekeepers there, while he 
represented Japan at a meeting of the Association of Southeast 
Asian Nations (ASEAN) post-ministerial conference. He has shown 
a particular interest in Myanmar [Burma], having visited the 
country and met with top junta leaders. 
  After graduating from Tokyo University, Kakizawa served for 
years as a Finance Ministry bureaucrat and spent time as an 
intern at the French Finance Ministry in Paris and a diplomat at 
the Japanese Embassy in Belgium. He ended his career as a 
bureaucrat in 1977 when he successfully ran for a seat in the 
House of Councillors as a candidate for the new Liberal Club, a 
splinter party from the Liberal Democratic Party (LDP). 
  In 1980, he was elected to the first of five terms in the 
House of Representatives. The following year he left the new 
Liberal Club, which disbanded in 1986, all of its former members 
rejoining the LDP. 
  After joining the LDP, he belonged to a faction led by 
former 
Foreign Minister Michio Watanabe and worked on foreign, defense 
and financial affairs. 
  Kakizawa launched the Liberal Party on April 20 along with 
five other LDP defectors and one independent amid the political 
turmoil sparked by the declaration of former Prime Minister 
Morihiro Hosokawa on April 8 that he would resign. 
  Kakizawa, hailing from Tokyo's No. 6 constituency, has been 
elected to the lower house five times. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-7192 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas082_a_94017" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-082 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  28 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Biographical Sketches of New Cabinet Members </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Biographical Sketches of New Cabinet Members </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Finance Minister Hirohisa Fujii </H4>

<F P=102> OW2804090094 Tokyo KYODO in English 0758 GMT 28 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2804090094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 28 KYODO -- Hirohisa Fujii retained 
his post as finance minister determined to get the fiscal 1994 
budget enacted and to press ahead with economic reform. 
  In the cabinet of Morihiro Hosokawa, Fujii championed a 
national welfare tax that was later scrapped, while opposing a 
proposal to introduce deficit-financing government bonds. The 7 
percent welfare tax plan was intended to replace the current 3 
percent consumption tax. 
  The plan met strong opposition from the Social Democratic 
Party (SDP) [of Japan -- SDPJ] -- the largest force in the 
Hosokawa coalition -- and was dumped the day after Hosokawa 
announced it in early February. 
  As a compromise, the ruling parties agreed to implement 
income tax cuts for one year only and financed by deficit bonds. 
Further tax reform measures are scheduled before the end of the 
year. 
  On the political front, Fujii faced tough questioning from 
the Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) over questionable political 
donations from a salt wholesalers' association which falls under 
the jurisdiction of the Finance Ministry. Because of this, it 
had been expected that Fujii would be replaced. 
  Other lingering problems for Fujii include prolonged 
economic 
recession and trade friction with the United States. Fujii 
recently said the economy is in a "delicate phase" and expressed 
confidence that the latest 15.25 trillion yen stimulus package 
coupled with the fiscal 1994 budget will "greatly" help put the 
economy on the path to full recovery. 
  While trying to take fiscal steps to boost domestic demand, 
Fujii repeatedly has tried to convince the United States that 
Japan intends to enact full-scale tax reform by the end of the 
year. The coalition parties are to detail the year-end tax 
reform package by June, fulfilling a government pledge in March. 
  Fujii, 61, won a seat in the lower House of Representatives 
last year as a member of Shinseito [Japan Renewal Party]. He 
defended the lower house seat once as a LDP member after moving 
from his twice-elected seat in the upper House of Councillors. 
  Fujii is known as the right arm of Shinseito strategist 
Ichiro Ozawa, with the left arm being International Trade and 
Industry Minister Hiroshi Kumagai. 
  Born in Tokyo, Fujii served as a career Finance Ministry 
bureaucrat after graduating from Tokyo University before 
starting his political carrier. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-7193 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas082_a_94018" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-082 </AU>
