<H3> <TI>   Biographical Sketches of New Cabinet Members </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Biographical Sketches of New Cabinet Members </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Labor Minister Kunio Hatoyama </H4>

<F P=102> OW2804082194 Tokyo KYODO in English 0735 GMT 28 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2804082194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 28 KYODO -- Newly appointed Labor 
Minister Kunio Hatoyama has a prominent family background in 
politics. 
  His great-grandfather Kazuo Hatoyama was a former lower 
house 
speaker, while his late grandfather Ichiro Hatoyama served as 
prime minister and his late father Iichiro was foreign minister. 
His elder brother Kunio is a lower house lawmaker who has 
served as deputy chief cabinet secretary. 
  Hatoyama, 45, an independent House of Representatives 
legislator, replaces Chikara Sakaguchi of Komeito [Clean 
Government Party] as labor minister. 
  After graduating from Tokyo University, Hatoyama became 
secretary to the late former Prime Minister Kakuei Tanaka. He 
won a lower house seat as an independent and later joined the 
LDP. 
  He was noted for crossing party lines to vote against the 
LDP 
government's abortive first attempt to introduce the consumption 
tax. 
  During the first administration of then Prime Minister 
Kiichi 
Miyazawa of the LDP from November 1991 to December 1992, 
Hatoyama served as education minister and proposed scrapping 
examinations prepared by the private firms, on the grounds the 
exams encouraged excessive competition among students to go to 
higher educational facilities. 
  He left the LDP in 1992 as the party's then largest faction 
led by former Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita broke up. 
  Hatoyama has been elected to the lower chamber six times. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS4-7200 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas082_a_94025" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-082 </AU>
Daily Report 
<DATE1>  28 Apr 1994 </DATE1>

