<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Biographical Sketches of New Cabinet Members </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Biographical Sketches of New Cabinet Members </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    National Land Agency Leader Sato </H4>

<F P=102> OW2804083594 Tokyo KYODO in English 0741 GMT 28 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW2804083594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, April 28 KYODO -- Newly appointed National 
Land Agency Chief Megumu Sato is known to have refused to 
sanction the execution of death row inmates when he was justice 
minister for about a year from December 1990. Sato, 70, has 
advocated that Japan should abolish the death penalty. 
  Sato, a House of Representatives legislator of Shinseito 
[Japan Renewal Party], a core political party in the coalition 
government led by new Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata, is also a 
Buddhist priest. 
  Japan, one of the few remaining developed countries with 
capital punishment, had not executed death row inmates for three 
years and four months from November 1989, but resumed hanging 
last year, putting three people to death in March and four in 
November. 
  Sato has been elected to the House of Representatives nine 
times since 1969 from the sixth constituency of Osaka 
Prefecture. Before becoming a politician, he was a bureaucrat 
at the Posts and Telecommunications Ministry and later served as 
posts and telecommunications minister from 1984 to 1985. 
  He was a member of the Liberal Democratic Party (LDP) -- the 
former ruling party now in opposition -- until last summer and 
once belonged to the LDP faction of late former Prime Minister 
Kakuei Tanaka. 
  Sato quit the LDP last June and formed Shinseito with other 
defectors including Hata. 
  His late father had served as Defense Agency chief and Osaka 
governor. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

